{"id":14880814,"mediaExerciseId":"db594b17-72dd-4079-b900-4b21736c7800","exerciseName":"19","chapterName":"3","chapterTitle":"Working with Financial Statements","groupId":612275,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":87,"solutions":[{"id":5963074,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are required to determine the company’s days’ sales in receivables.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":61,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/6e7b6379c9cdda0a4cd5d3cfa7f33537/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/6e7b6379c9cdda0a4cd5d3cfa7f33537/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we begin, let us first define days’ sales in receivables.\n\n**Days’ sales in receivables** shows the number of days it takes to collect the company's accounts receivable.\n\nThe formula is denoted as follows:\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Days’ sales in receivables}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Accounts Receivable}} {\\text{Net Credit Sales}} \\times {\\text{365 days}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":231,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/be3441418a3bb9bee85d44f1d3b23a45/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":118,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/be3441418a3bb9bee85d44f1d3b23a45/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we can determine the days' sales in receivables, first we need to determine the net sales by using the profit margin ratio.\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Profit margin}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Net Income}} {\\text{Net Sales}}\\\\ \\\\\n6.8\\%& = \\frac{\\$432,000} {?}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":286,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/0c5fb402478df717488cf97e62722ed6/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":144,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/0c5fb402478df717488cf97e62722ed6/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"By deriving the formula, the net sales can be computed as follows:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Net Sales}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Net Income}} {\\text{Profit Margin}}\\\\ \\\\\n& = \\frac{\\$432,000} {6.8\\%}\\\\ \\\\\n& = \\frac{\\$432,000} {0.068}\\\\ \\\\\n&=\\boxed{\\$6,352,941.18}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nAs can be seen, the net sales is $6,352,941.18.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Since 65 percent of sales are on credit, the net credit sales can be computed as follows:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Net Credit Sales}& = \\text{Net Sales} \\times \\text{65\\%}\\\\ \\\\\n&=\\$6,352,941.18\\times0.65\\\\ \\\\\n&=\\boxed{\\$4,129,411.77}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nAs can be seen, the net credit sales is $4,129,411.77.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we proceed, let us first define receivables turnover.\n\n**Receivables turnover** is used to measure the effectiveness of a company in extending credit as well as collecting debts.\n\nThe formula is denoted as follows:\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Receivables turnover}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Net Credit Sales}} {\\text{Average Accounts Receivable}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":236,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/235b4d6e7c68d1c64af8965d49862232/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":120,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/235b4d6e7c68d1c64af8965d49862232/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"To determine the receivables turnover:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Receivables turnover}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Net Credit Sales}} {\\text{Average Accounts Receivable}}\\\\ \\\\\n& = \\frac{\\$4,129,411.77} {\\$119,630.00}\\\\ \\\\\n&= \\boxed{34.52}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nAs can be seen, the receivables turnover is 34.52.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":408,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/08f08c69ec9becd48e36dcdcb89a1838/lateximg_large.png","width":872},"regular":{"height":206,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/08f08c69ec9becd48e36dcdcb89a1838/lateximg.png","width":435}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7},{"columns":[{"text":"Finally, we can now determine the days' sales in receivables:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Days’ sales in receivables}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{365 days}} {\\text{Receivables turnover}}\\\\ \\\\\n& = \\frac{365} {34.52} \\\\ \\\\\n&= \\boxed{10.57}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nIn conclusion, the days’ sales in receivables is 10.57.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":393,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/e44aaed39be08d4e278066dc6ffc0a33/lateximg_large.png","width":842},"regular":{"height":198,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/e44aaed39be08d4e278066dc6ffc0a33/lateximg.png","width":421}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":8},{"columns":[{"text":"10.57","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":22,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/4efeee9033f4cdde2c8804879e3d3bce/lateximg_large.png","width":66},"regular":{"height":12,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/f69b278a1fddb2a5813c99cee4b309a9/4efeee9033f4cdde2c8804879e3d3bce/lateximg.png","width":35}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":true,"stepNumber":9}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"d9dca027-49ba-489e-8752-c48c3ec01e68","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":9}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880815,"exerciseName":"20","page":87,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"b2cd23cd-3ec5-4b03-b334-2ac937d43a8b","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-3-questions-and-problems-20-b2cd23cd-3ec5-4b03-b334-2ac937d43a8b"},{"id":14880816,"exerciseName":"21","page":87,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"13e48e44-e47d-4c36-b7d5-67d2abcbc260","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-978125991895